WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.400
Hi everyone, I'm Irene. I was an intern with RStudio last summer working with the Tidyverse

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:20.400
team, specifically with Jenny Brine, who many of you know. And now I'm based in Tel Aviv.

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:26.280
And today I'll be talking about the data science puzzles I was building last summer, and some

00:00:26.280 --> 00:00:31.320
of the extra concepts that we were trying to also convey through these puzzles. Is it

00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:40.119
really echoey? No? Yes? Okay. Well, sorry. And so this story really starts over a year

00:00:40.119 --> 00:00:45.320
ago in December. I was supposed to be writing my thesis or something. Instead I was drawn

00:00:45.320 --> 00:00:50.759
into these coding challenges online known as the advent of code. And as you might guess

00:00:50.759 --> 00:00:57.160
from the name, these are a series of puzzles, daily puzzles, from December 1st to the 25th.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:01:02.880
And they cover all kinds of different computer science concepts, but in really fun ways.

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:07.320
And just to give you a sense of what that looks like, this is just a screenshot from

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:11.519
that page. You have some puzzle text telling you what the problem is. You know, there's

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:16.800
a robot running up to you and there's some tragedy that you have to solve. At the very

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:21.080
bottom there's a link to your unique puzzle input. So maybe there's just a lot of garbled

00:01:21.080 --> 00:01:25.360
text that you have to somehow parse. And then at the very bottom is a little text box for

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:30.760
you to enter your answer and, you know, get your little star. And so these puzzles can

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:37.800
be solved in any number of different programming languages. As an R user, I used R. And I found

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:43.959
that I was using R in very unfamiliar and unnatural ways. But I was still able to solve

00:01:43.959 --> 00:01:48.879
a lot of the puzzles. A little did I know at the time, but Jenny

00:01:48.879 --> 00:01:54.040
Bryan was also solving these puzzles around the same time. And she took that feeling one

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:59.360
step further. She thought, well, these puzzles are a lot of fun, but why don't we make a

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:05.080
set of puzzles that highlight what R and the tidyverse are actually good at? In other words,

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:11.279
how about we make a set of puzzles that focus on the idea of messy data and tidying it up?

00:02:11.279 --> 00:02:16.240
And so that's how this project was born. It's currently known, oh, as the tidies of

00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:24.199
March. It looked better on my computer. So they've become a series of bite-sized puzzles

00:02:24.199 --> 00:02:30.240
that focus on core data science skills as championed by the tidyverse set of packages.

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:34.399
I think I forgot to mention at the beginning, there is a GitHub repo with nicer looking

