slides that will be linked to at the end as well.

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:47.360
And so just before I move on, I wanted to quickly tell you about the name. I think the

00:02:48.559 --> 00:02:53.199
phrase beware the Ides of March is maybe familiar to some of you. It comes from the tragedy

00:02:53.199 --> 00:02:57.839
of Julius Caesar by Shakespeare. And so you have this fortune teller coming up to Caesar

00:02:57.839 --> 00:03:04.839
saying beware the Ides of March, which means beware the 15th of March. Caesar is like,

00:03:04.839 --> 00:03:11.279
okay, whatever, dude. And of course, come 15th of March, Caesar is assassinated, more

00:03:11.279 --> 00:03:17.080
tragedy ensues, and I think the moral of the story is that you and your data do not have

00:03:17.080 --> 00:03:24.080
to fall into the same fate. You can avert tragedy by using the tidyverse and tidy tools.

00:03:25.080 --> 00:03:30.119
And so for this project, we had a number of different goals. We had some more general

00:03:30.119 --> 00:03:34.679
goals. We wanted to build up a community around these puzzles to have a space where people

00:03:34.679 --> 00:03:41.679
can share their solutions and see other people's solutions, whether it's in tidyverse or Python.

00:03:41.839 --> 00:03:46.960
And then we wanted to be able to create a bank of solutions to these discrete data wrangling

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:53.960
problems. But beyond that, we also wanted to impart on people some very specific skills.

00:03:54.559 --> 00:04:01.440
First off, we wanted to help people exercise their wrangling skills for beginners, introducing

00:04:01.440 --> 00:04:06.000
them to a lot of these different packages for more advanced users, showing them some

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.520
of these lesser known functions within these packages. And beyond that, we also wanted

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:18.519
to promote the concept of workflow and project management. That's supposed to be a little

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:26.519
Git icon. And in order to do that, what we did was rather than just have this web interface

00:04:30.279 --> 00:04:36.559
where you can just go off and use whatever IDE or whatever tool you wanted, we were going

00:04:36.559 --> 00:04:43.559
to build an R package that guided you through that process and guided you through and modeled

00:04:44.559 --> 00:04:51.000
some of these best practices so that you can start to internalize some of those things.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.559
And so this is more or less what it looks like. Like with any other package, you start

00:04:54.559 --> 00:05:01.320
with a library call, you start with an initialized puzzles function, and you pass it a directory

00:05:01.320 --> 00:05:06.600
name. And what it does is it creates a new project for you and then sets you up with

00:05:06.600 --> 00:05:11.640
a number of different files. We'll just take a quick look at that here.

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:18.760
So first, before anything else, if you use this R mediated route or this R mediated experience,

00:05:19.559 --> 00:05:24.399
we force a few things on you. We force you to use an R project. We think it's a very

00:05:24.399 --> 00:05:31.399
good idea to use these projects and keep all the relevant files in one place, keep it portable

00:05:31.399 --> 00:05:36.920
so that you can access those same files from a different computer and it will just work.

00:05:37.519 --> 00:05:44.160
And use this logo in the bottom corner here because it was a big inspiration for this

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:51.160
package. It focuses a lot on workflows and on making some of those kind of more meticulous

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:59.160
tasks a little bit more easy to do. You see here there are a number of other files.

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:06.640
The dot puzzle file stores some of your user information. You have 01 underscore pets.

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:11.040
That's your first puzzle. And as the days go on, you can download additional puzzles

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:16.119
as additional folders. And then you have a read me. So if you now put this project on

00:06:16.119 --> 00:06:23.119
a GitHub repository, you have that already set up for you and automatically generated.

00:06:23.279 --> 00:06:30.279
And so now if we click into the puzzle folder, we see a number of things. Maybe the first

00:06:30.359 --> 00:06:36.480
thing you notice is the naming convention. You see that everything starts with a 01 underscore.

00:06:36.480 --> 00:06:41.079
We use an underscore rather than a space. We use that leading zero so that once we have

00:06:41.079 --> 00:06:46.739
more than ten puzzles, it will still order nicely. So basically we're following and modeling

00:06:46.739 --> 00:06:51.760
the principles of having names that are machine readable, human readable, and that play well

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:57.880
with default ordering. And these files specifically, I think you can see here, you have one file

00:06:57.880 --> 00:07:03.320
that's the data file. That's the file that you need to wrangle. In this case, it's an

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:08.040
Excel file. We have a solution script that's been started for you, and I'll show that in

00:07:08.040 --> 00:07:12.239
a second. And then you have the puzzle text. And so that's that problem that you're trying

00:07:12.239 --> 00:07:17.320
to solve. Like that's, you know, Johnny has some problem with his microwave data, and

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:23.760
you have to solve it. And so this is what the solution script looks like. There are

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:28.480
a number of things that we've kind of put into here. You don't necessarily have to understand

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:33.679
it all, but I'll point out a few here. First, we have this prepopulated path. Because of

00:07:33.679 --> 00:07:38.239
this very rigid structure, we know where everything is. We can just populate that data path, and

00:07:38.239 --> 00:07:42.839
you can choose the import function you want to use.

00:07:42.839 --> 00:07:48.239
There are a few other things. We use here here so that we can use the same relative

00:07:48.239 --> 00:07:54.079
path both in your R scripts and in your R Markdown files. R Markdown and R scripts,

00:07:54.079 --> 00:07:59.559
they understand the home directory in a slightly different way, and this makes it just work

00:07:59.559 --> 00:08:07.299
across different file types. This weird notation here with this hashtag apostrophe and hashtag

00:08:07.299 --> 00:08:12.899
plus, that allows you to have an R script that functions in the same way as an R Markdown

00:08:12.899 --> 00:08:18.820
file, where you can have text mixed in with your code. And then the last bit that I point

00:08:18.820 --> 00:08:24.579
out here is this options tidyverse.quiet equals true. That just turns off all the tidyverse

00:08:24.579 --> 00:08:30.179
attach messages so that when we have this rendered file, we just have that library call

00:08:30.179 --> 00:08:37.280
without all those extra messages. And so jumping back to the README, this is what it

00:08:37.280 --> 00:08:42.219
looks like. Now that you have a sense of what that repository looks like, here it doesn't

